<item>
  <title>The Laundry Quarter Paradox: A Birthday Problem Estimation</title>
  <dc:creator>Connor Lockhart</dc:creator>
  <link>https://conair94.github.io/Quarto/posts/laundry-quarter-estimation/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 





<p>Have you ever wondered if the quarter you just dropped into the laundry machine is one you’ve held before? A friend recently asked me this very question. It sounds like a needle-in-a-haystack scenario, but when we look at it through the lens of the <strong>Generalized Birthday Problem</strong>, the odds might be higher than you’d expect.</p>
<section id="the-math" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-math">The Math</h2>
<p>To estimate this, we consider: - <strong><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n"></strong>: The total number of quarters you’ve handled over a period of time. - <strong><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N"></strong>: The total pool of quarters in circulation in your local area (e.g., your metro area).</p>
<p>The probability <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?P"> that at least two quarters in your sample of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n"> are the same is given by:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?P(n,%20N)%20%5Capprox%201%20-%20e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac%7Bn(n-1)%7D%7B2N%7D%7D"></p>
<p>For small values of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n%5E2/2N">, we can use the Taylor series approximation:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?P(n,%20N)%20%5Capprox%20%5Cfrac%7Bn%5E2%7D%7B2N%7D"></p>
</section>
